#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800 Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.rmk: Bird singing from about 20 feet up in tree in a mostly forested area.  Another Wood Thrush was singing in the distance.  Recorded as iPhone voice memo (.m4a) and converted to .mp3.

I heard the bird first. There were also many Swainson's Thrushes around and singing, but this has the ee-oo-lay of Wood Thrush.  After much searching I saw the bird (but it was not singing then.) It was about 10 feet off the ground, hiding in foliage - a heavily spotted thrush down through flanks, with rusty, reddish back and streaking in cheek, and bright white underparts.
I had heard the bird on April 14 and went back on the 15th to try for a better recording.

Started hearing Swainson's Thrush song around 18:50 in very dense woods. Knowing there was a potential Wood Thrush in the area, I played tape twice and the Swainson's call came closer but still not within sight. I decided to hike in and try and find the source. As I was hiking in, I heard a different song being sung directly above me. I immediately recognized this as Wood Thrush. The bird was very close but I could not get a visual. It sang for about 1 minute and I decided to quickly get my phone out to record the sound in case this was the only evidence I could obtain. The recording starts out with SWTH and the loudest bird is the WOTH.
ID certainty 90%. (Archiv. tape 165 side B track 34 seq. A)

recordings.rmk: Three cuts pasted together; first cut is one bird, which gives two different "kuck-kuck" series followed by some "peen" calls. The second cut has one or two more birds joining in. By the third cut there is a chorus of "kuck-kuck" and "whit-whit" from all over. Our presence may have  solicited this, but I am not sure as they continued to call after we'd left.

Poor/ competition with Carolina Wren/ others + traffic noise. 70 degrees, light rain just before recording. Count of Wood Thrush for this migrant trap for the morning was 22 birds- with at least 10 in the general area where recording was made. Narrow (.1-.3 mi) but densely wooded strip along Red River- recorded at woods edge adjacent parking lot.  Several birds were frequently singing- one in recording. Playback was not needed or used early on here.
